What is Git?
Git is a Version Control System (VCS).
Think of it as a time machine for your code.

Without Git:
project.py
project_final.py
project_final_final.py
project_final_latest.py
project_final_latest_new.py

With Git:
Version 1
Version 2
Version 3
Version 4
You can go back to any version whenever you want.

Git vs GitHub
Many beginners confuse them.
Git
Software installed on your computer.
Used for:
Tracking changes
Creating versions
Branching
Merging

GitHub
Website where Git repositories are stored online.
Examples:
GitHub
GitLab

Think:
Git      = Engine
GitHub   = Cloud Storage
Complete Git Workflow

Every day you will do:
Create File
    ↓
git add
    ↓
git commit
    ↓
git push

Step 1: git init
What it does
Creates a Git repository.

Example:
mkdir MyProject
cd MyProject
git init

Output:
Initialized empty Git repository
What happens internally?
Git creates a hidden folder:
.git
Structure:
MyProject
│
├── app.py
└── .git

The .git folder stores:
History
Commits
Branches
Configurations

Without .git, Git doesn't exist.

Check hidden files:
ls -a
or in Windows:
dir /a

Step 2: git status
Most important command.
git status
Example:
Untracked files:
    app.py

Git tells you:

New files
Modified files
Staged files

Always run:
git status
before committing.
Understanding Git Areas
Git has 3 major areas.

Working Directory
      ↓
Staging Area
      ↓
Repository

Example:
app.py
You edit it.
Currently:
Working Directory

Step 3: git add
Moves files to staging area.
git add app.py
Now:
Working Directory
      ↓
Staging Area

Add everything:

git add .

Meaning:
Stage all changes

Check:
git status
Output:
Changes to be committed
Why Staging Area Exists?

Imagine:
You changed:
app.py
README.md
notes.txt

But only want to commit:
app.py

Then:
git add app.py
Only that file is staged.

Step 4: git commit
Creates a snapshot.
git commit -m "Added login feature"

Think:

Take Photo
Git saves current state forever.

Visual:
Commit 1
    ↓
Commit 2
    ↓
Commit 3

Each commit has a unique ID.
Example:

4f9a6e2
Commit Messages

Bad:

git commit -m "update"

Good:

git commit -m "Added binary search solution"

Good:

git commit -m "Fixed login validation bug"
Step 5: git log

Shows history.

git log

Output:

commit a12345
Author: Asmita
Date: ...

Added binary search

Compact:

git log --oneline

Example:

a12345 Added binary search
b67890 Created project
Step 6: GitHub Repository

Create repository on GitHub.

Example:

LeetCode-Solutions

GitHub provides:

git remote add origin https://github.com/username/repo.git
What is Origin?

Remote nickname.

origin

means:

GitHub repository address

Check:

git remote -v
Step 7: git push

Uploads commits to GitHub.

git push origin main

Meaning:

push → upload

origin → GitHub

main → branch

Visual:

Local PC
    ↓
GitHub
Step 8: git clone

Copy repository from GitHub.

git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git

Result:

Entire repository downloaded
Step 9: git pull

Download latest changes.

git pull origin main

Meaning:

GitHub
    ↓
Your Computer
Branches

Default branch:

main

Think:

Main Road

Create side road:

git branch feature-login

Switch:

git checkout feature-login

Modern way:

git switch feature-login

Create + Switch:

git switch -c feature-login

Visual:

main
  |
  |
feature-login
Merge

After completing feature:

git switch main
git merge feature-login

Result:

feature-login
      \
       \
main ---- merged
Git Ignore

Prevent files from being tracked.

Create:

.gitignore

Example:

__pycache__/
.env
node_modules/

Git ignores them.

Undo Commands
Unstage
git restore --staged app.py

Removes from staging area.

Discard Changes
git restore app.py

Danger:

Deletes modifications.

View Differences
git diff

Shows:

- old code
+ new code
Rename File
git mv old.py new.py
Delete File
git rm file.py
